Was this what originally attracted you to your 
work on the Colorado River, or was it vice versa?

24:48.997 --> 24:53.242
Well, I got interested in the Colorado River for a 
very curious reason. I was plotting the total

24:54.043 --> 25:06.699
dissolved solids of the Colorado River one time, 
and several other rivers, including the Indus, as

24:54.043 --> 25:06.699
a function of stream flow, annual stream flow. And 
it turns out that instead of that line of plot of

25:07.640 --> 25:17.873
total dissolved solids per year and total water 
flow per year, extrapolating through the

25:18.697 --> 25:30.393
zero-zero axis, which is, say, zero dissolved 
solids transported at zero flow, it goes through

25:18.697 --> 25:30.393
the dissolved solid axis at rather high level. 
It's an inclined line, which says, in the case of

25:30.713 --> 25:38.984
the Colorado, that at zero flow, it's 
transporting 3,600,000 tons of salt. Well, the

25:39.965 --> 25:46.594
only possible explanation for such a decent 
river, like the Mississippi, goes through the

25:39.965 --> 25:46.594
zero-zero axis. But both the Indus and the 
Colorado do not. The only possible explanation

25:50.292 --> 25:56.300
for this is that there are brine springs feeding 
into the rivers. Brine springs, not salt springs,

25:56.680 --> 26:02.147
but concentrated brines, which are continuously 
flowing. So that as the river goes down a year of low

26:03.629 --> 26:10.978
flow, the slant is higher.

26:12.376 --> 26:15.961
We start hunting for those springs, which we 
assume must exist. And we found none of them in the

26:16.061 --> 26:20.788
hydrological literature at all. We found them in 
the anthropological literature. The Indians

26:24.414 --> 26:28.480
knew about these brine springs flowing into 
Colorado. And the first one we looked for was a

26:28.500 --> 26:38.294
great series of volcano-like structures of pure 
salt with pure saturated brine flowing down into

26:28.500 --> 26:38.294
Colorado. 600,000 tons a year. And I thought, you 
know, the hydrological mythology is the river

26:42.650 --> 26:51.323
supplies you with water that God has determined 
the quality of. That is now your problem. Nobody

26:52.544 --> 26:56.650
ever inquires as to how it got that quality. So now 
here's just this one spring. 600,000 tons is

26:58.493 --> 27:04.922
enough to put 15,000 acres out of existence every 
year by salination. But it's a small flow. Why not

27:06.713 --> 27:16.543
build a little brick retainer and pump the damn 
stuff back up on the mesa or inject it into the

27:06.713 --> 27:16.543
ground and keep it out of the Colorado? Can't get 
anybody interested in that. Reclamation

27:18.826 --> 27:21.008
Department doesn't do that sort of thing. 
Agriculture Department care less. That's not

27:23.110 --> 27:24.852
part of their problem. And so it still flows into 
the Colorado as far as I know.

27:32.160 --> 27:35.303
And there are undoubtedly six more like that. And 
out of curiosity, you think anthropological

27:36.937 --> 27:41.162
sites can locate these? That's how we locate it. 
That's marvelous.

27:46.368 --> 27:59.383
Because the Indians had a real mythology about the 
trek, the salt trek, which was kind of a young

27:46.368 --> 27:59.383
manhood trek to go down in this great canyon and 
climb down these cliffs and gather the salt and

27:46.368 --> 27:59.383
bring it back. And that's all recorded in 1896. 
That's where we found it. We even found the old

28:05.588 --> 28:17.100
ladder that the first man who went down there early 
in this century had built to get down one of these

28:05.588 --> 28:17.100
cliffs, all full of salt drift and crystals of 
salt. What made you decide to check

28:17.121 --> 28:19.663
anthropological literature? Well, it's obvious 
that if you're going to find out what the Indian

28:20.024 --> 28:25.590
names of these damn streams are, they'd surely 
know whether they had salt in them or not.

28:29.198 --> 28:31.061
And, of course, the Indus does the same thing. I 
mean, it's easy. There's a place called Salt

28:32.243 --> 28:34.868
Mountain or Salt Hill. It's by Sargodha. And it 
flows into the Indus. It's salt water.

28:44.465 --> 28:45.748
Anyway, that's only part of it. But it's 
interesting, it seems to me. And it's an

28:49.835 --> 28:52.219
interesting commentary on our bureaucracy.

